WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.700 --> 00:00:02.840
All right. Good morning, everybody.

2
00:00:03.720 --> 00:00:05.720
My name is Evanthea Rousos-Torres.

3
00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:09.390
I am an assistant professor of medicine from the University of Southern California.

4
00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:13.760
It's my pleasure to welcome you to AACR's Plenary Session Four, Advances

5
00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:14.550
in Immunotherapy.

6
00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:18.270
This morning, we're going to hear from four investigators representing their

7
00:00:18.280 --> 00:00:21.980
respective research teams who will present data from early phase trials

8
00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:25.800
investigating novel checkpoint and other immunotherapies in various different

9
00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:29.500
solid tumor types, and four different discussants who will discuss their results.

10
00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:34.260
Like to introduce yourself?

11
00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:38.240
Sure. I'm Ryan Sullivan from Mass General Brigham Cancer Institute, and I'm

12
00:00:38.250 --> 00:00:41.340
very excited for this plenary session.

13
00:00:41.380 --> 00:00:44.949
And I'm going to stop talking so you can hear the real great science and

14
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.420
discussants for the rest of the time.

15
00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:49.060
Great.

16
00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:53.940
All right. So I'd like to first welcome our first speaker,

17
00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:58.310
Dr. Alberto Giovanni Leone from the Fondazione

18
00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:02.280
Istituto Nazionale dei Tumori di Milano, from Milan, Italy.

19
00:01:03.280 --> 00:01:06.750
He'll be presenting the final results of the INFINITY study investigating

20
00:01:06.750 --> 00:01:10.740
tremelimumab and durvalumab as definitive non-operative management for

21
00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:12.320
MSI-high gastric cancers.

22
00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:24.340
Good morning, everyone, and thank you for being here, and thanks to the

23
00:01:24.420 --> 00:01:26.500
AACR for the big opportunity.

24
00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:31.360
Today, I'm going to present the final results of cohort

25
00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:32.940
two of INFINITY trial

26
00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:37.780
evaluating a non-operative management strategy with tremelimumab

27
00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:41.580
plus durvalumab in patients with resectable

28
00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:45.140
MSI high gastric and gastroesophageal junction cancer.

29
00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:48.240
I have no disclosures.

30
00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:52.420
So let's start with the clinical context.

31
00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:57.200
In resectable gastric and gastroesophageal junction adenocarcinoma,

32
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.580
MSI-high is associated with better survival,

33
00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:04.920
but also with a lack of benefit from chemotherapy.

34
00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:10.120
At the same time, we know that these tumors are highly sensitive

35
00:02:10.200 --> 00:02:13.640
to immune checkpoint blockade. For example, in cohort

36
00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:16.100
one of our INFINITY trial,

37
00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:20.500
a short course of neoadjuvant dual

38
00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:24.510
immunotherapy with the STRIDE regimen, tremelimumab plus durvalumab,

39
00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:29.080
led to 60% of pathological complete

40
00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:29.860
responses

41
00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:33.880
and 80% of major pathological responses.

42
00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:37.680
And so the key clinical question became, if

43
00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:39.380
responses are this deep,

44
00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:42.580
do all patients still need surgery?

45
00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:46.000
And this was the rationale for cohort two.

46
00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:50.230
We designed this trial to test whether a non-operative

47
00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:50.880
management

48
00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:52.860
could be a safe

49
00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:57.600
and effective strategy for those patients achieving a clinical

50
00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:01.820
complete response after only three months of dual immunotherapy.

51
00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.520
This was the trial design. INFINITY was a Phase

52
00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:11.940
2 singular multi-cohort trial.

53
00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:16.700
Eligible patients had gastric or gastroesophageal

54
00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:20.580
adenocarcinoma were MSI-high with

55
00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:23.840
a deficient mismatch repair status, EBV negative,

56
00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:28.300
and with a T2 or higher disease and any nodal

57
00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:28.860
status.

58
00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:34.780
Patients received STRIDE regimen consisting of tremelimumab,

59
00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:38.600
the anti-CDL4 on day one as a single

60
00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:42.440
flat dose of 300 milligrams, and durvalumab, the

61
00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:43.190
anti-PD-L1,

62
00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:48.180
1,500 milligrams as a flat dose every four weeks

63
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.880
for three cycles for a total duration of three months of therapy.

64
00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:57.380
Between weeks 12 and 14, all patients underwent a

65
00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:59.520
strict multimodal restaging.

66
00:04:00.890 --> 00:04:03.940
Now, in cohort one, all patients underwent surgery

67
00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:06.140
regardless of their clinical response.

68
00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:11.250
In cohort two, only patients with an incomplete

69
00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:15.040
response underwent salvage surgery, whereas patients who

70
00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:18.630
achieved a clinical complete response, and later on we will see how we

71
00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.579
defined the clinical complete response,

72
00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:24.220
proceeded to the non-operative management pathway.

73
00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:28.380
And this pathway consisted of an intensive

74
00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:32.220
surveillance every 12 weeks up to two years with a CT

75
00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:32.700
scan,

76
00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:37.480
endoscopy with bite-on-bite biopsies, at least six

77
00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:41.280
bite-on-bite biopsies, and tissue-informed ctDNA assessment

78
00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:42.720
when technically feasible.

79
00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:47.660
Importantly, after the results of cohort one

80
00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:52.230
and following review by an independent data monitoring committee,

81
00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:57.200
patients with a T4 disease were excluded from enrollment

82
00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:00.980
in cohort two due to their low probability of achieving a

83
00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:04.200
clinical complete response after only three months of

84
00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:05.080
immunotherapy.

85
00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:12.180
The primary endpoint was the two-year clinical complete response

86
00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:15.260
rate without salvage surgery.

87
00:05:16.460 --> 00:05:20.220
Now, this is critical. Clinical complete response was not

88
00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:24.060
defined on one test only. It required all of the following to be

89
00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:27.080
negative: a CT scan, a PET scan,

90
00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:31.370
EGD with endoscopic ultrasound and bite-on-bite

91
00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:34.550
biopsies, and tissue-informed ctDNA.

92
00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:39.300
So it was a composite clinical, pathological, and molecular

93
00:05:39.460 --> 00:05:40.040
definition.

94
00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:45.240
Secondary endpoints included progression-free survival, overall survival,

95
00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:49.060
gastrectomy-free survival, as well as safety, quality of life,

96
00:05:49.430 --> 00:05:51.980
and exploratory translational analysis.

97
00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:57.510
From January to December 2023,

98
00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:01.860
we enrolled 18 patients, and 18 patients started treatment.

99
00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:06.240
However, one patient withdrew consent after only one cycle of

100
00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:10.050
immunotherapy and has been lost to follow-upSo

101
00:06:10.090 --> 00:06:13.930
eventually, 17 patients were evaluable for the primary endpoint.

102
00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:17.970
The table on the right shows the baseline features for the

103
00:06:18.010 --> 00:06:19.610
intention-to-treat population.

104
00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:23.730
And now let's move to the key results.

105
00:06:25.270 --> 00:06:28.230
The clinical complete response rate at two years was

106
00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:29.790
71%.

107
00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:32.090
In details,

108
00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:36.650
13 out of 17 patients achieved

109
00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:38.290
clinical complete response

110
00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:42.860
at the restaging between weeks 12 and 14 and

111
00:06:42.970 --> 00:06:45.610
proceeded to the non-operative management pathway.

112
00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:51.010
Among these, only one patient had a

113
00:06:51.050 --> 00:06:54.950
locoregional recurrence four months after completion

114
00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:56.070
of the immunotherapy,

115
00:06:58.390 --> 00:07:02.210
has been surgically salvaged, and

116
00:07:03.010 --> 00:07:05.230
has remained free of disease since then.

117
00:07:07.610 --> 00:07:10.460
Four patients did not achieve clinical complete response,

118
00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:14.110
so they underwent immediate salvage surgery.

119
00:07:14.589 --> 00:07:18.130
And among these, one patient actually had a

120
00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:21.950
pathological complete response on primary tumor, but not in the lymph

121
00:07:21.990 --> 00:07:22.250
nodes.

122
00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:27.310
Two patients had a moderate pathological response corresponding

123
00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:29.850
to a Becker tumor regression grade of two,

124
00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:35.270
and one patient had a poor pathological response corresponding to a Becker

125
00:07:35.310 --> 00:07:36.170
grade of three.

126
00:07:37.310 --> 00:07:37.930
Importantly,

127
00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:43.070
three out of four of these patients had a positive tissue-informed

128
00:07:43.130 --> 00:07:46.750
ctDNA at the restaging, whereas only one patient had a

129
00:07:46.790 --> 00:07:48.530
ctDNA negative.

130
00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:53.350
And here we can see the survival outcomes.

131
00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:58.170
After a median follow-up of 27.1 months and

132
00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:00.790
with a minimum follow-up of 24 months,

133
00:08:02.050 --> 00:08:03.570
the results were very encouraging.

134
00:08:04.250 --> 00:08:06.690
The 24-month progression-free survival was

135
00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:08.650
94.1%.

136
00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:13.290
The 24-month overall survival was 100%,

137
00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:17.530
and the 24-month gastrectomy-free survival was

138
00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:21.630
70.6%. So no patients died, no patients

139
00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:25.290
required additional systemic treatment, nor radiotherapy.

140
00:08:28.730 --> 00:08:31.150
The treatment was overall well-tolerated.

141
00:08:32.191 --> 00:08:36.130
Seventy-two percent of patients had adverse events of any

142
00:08:36.170 --> 00:08:40.150
grade, but only three patients, which is 17% of the

143
00:08:40.170 --> 00:08:44.130
intention-to-treat population, had a grade 3 adverse event.

144
00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:48.050
And in detail, we observed one case of hyperthyroidism,

145
00:08:48.430 --> 00:08:52.150
two cases of increased gamma-glutamyl transferase, and one

146
00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:56.140
case of colitis. All of these adverse events were

147
00:08:56.170 --> 00:08:59.450
treated as per protocol and completely resolved.

148
00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:04.430
No grade four or five adverse events occurred,

149
00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:07.640
and just one month delay in durvalumab

150
00:09:07.770 --> 00:09:11.610
administration due to immune-related grade two

151
00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:14.850
nephritis was reported in one patient.

152
00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:19.290
No cases of treatment discontinuation was reported.

153
00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:24.650
And now let's see the quality of life results.

154
00:09:25.030 --> 00:09:28.910
Quality of life was assessed using validated patient-reported

155
00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:29.970
outcome instruments,

156
00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:34.710
and these assessments were performed at the baseline, during treatment

157
00:09:34.730 --> 00:09:38.450
at cycle two and three, and after treatment at the restaging time

158
00:09:38.530 --> 00:09:38.830
point.

159
00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:44.350
Overall quality of life was preserved throughout all the patient's

160
00:09:44.390 --> 00:09:47.350
history without any clinically significant

161
00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:50.530
deterioration across all the global or

162
00:09:50.790 --> 00:09:52.750
functional or symptoms scales.

163
00:09:55.910 --> 00:09:57.810
Let's move to the exploratory analysis.

164
00:09:59.390 --> 00:10:03.170
In addition to the tissue-informed ctDNA analysis, which

165
00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:07.230
was used to define clinical complete response, as I said

166
00:10:07.290 --> 00:10:07.630
before,

167
00:10:08.450 --> 00:10:11.370
we performed plasma-only ctDNA

168
00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:14.990
analysis with a panel which hasn't been yet

169
00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:18.650
validated for gastric cancer, so the results are totally exploratory.

170
00:10:19.950 --> 00:10:23.810
At the baseline with this panel, ctDNA was detectable in

171
00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:27.290
13 of the 17 patients, and among these,

172
00:10:28.150 --> 00:10:29.330
84%

173
00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:34.350
of patients had a complete clearance of ctDNA

174
00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:38.090
after treatment. Whereas those patients who were negative

175
00:10:38.470 --> 00:10:41.510
at the baseline remained undetectable even after treatment.

176
00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:47.590
As we can see from the figure in the middle, higher baseline ctDNA

177
00:10:47.650 --> 00:10:51.630
levels were associated with a lower probability

178
00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:54.990
of achieving clinical complete response between weeks 12 and 14,

179
00:10:55.590 --> 00:10:59.540
but with a p-value of 0.06, so not statistically significant

180
00:10:59.550 --> 00:11:01.750
due to low numbers of our trial.

181
00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:06.730
And the figure on the right shows that ctDNA

182
00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:10.750
status at the restaging time point predicted

183
00:11:10.970 --> 00:11:14.930
failure of achieving clinical complete response with a

184
00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:18.750
sensitivity of 50% and a specificity of

185
00:11:18.950 --> 00:11:22.790
100%. So not perfect sensitivity, but when

186
00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:25.150
positive, high, very highly informative.

187
00:11:28.390 --> 00:11:30.590
And finally, let's move to the transcriptomics.

188
00:11:31.830 --> 00:11:35.450
Even within MSI-high tumors, we observed

189
00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:38.130
substantial biological heterogeneity.

190
00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:42.890
Among tumor samples collected at the baseline,

191
00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:44.930
we identified

192
00:11:45.890 --> 00:11:49.790
299 differentially expressed genes between

193
00:11:49.810 --> 00:11:52.910
tumor samples from patients who achieved clinical complete

194
00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:55.530
response versus those who did not.

195
00:11:56.770 --> 00:12:00.000
And in detail, tumor samples from responders showed

196
00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.650
upregulations of those genes involved in cytotoxic

197
00:12:03.730 --> 00:12:06.750
activity and immune recognition.

198
00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:10.748
Whereas tumor samples from non-respondersShowed

199
00:12:10.818 --> 00:12:14.258
upregulation of those genes involved in stromal

200
00:12:14.318 --> 00:12:18.098
activation and epithelial-mesenchymal transition

201
00:12:18.158 --> 00:12:19.138
related programs.

202
00:12:20.798 --> 00:12:24.158
The figure on the right shows the results from our deconvolution

203
00:12:24.198 --> 00:12:27.098
analysis of bulk RNA sequencing data.

204
00:12:27.588 --> 00:12:30.978
And we can see that higher baseline myeloid

205
00:12:31.038 --> 00:12:34.008
infiltration was evident in tumor samples from

206
00:12:34.078 --> 00:12:37.948
non-responders with a concordant trend toward an

207
00:12:37.978 --> 00:12:41.678
enrichment of M2-like macrophages, as we had

208
00:12:41.698 --> 00:12:45.638
already observed from tumor samples of non-responders from cohort

209
00:12:45.758 --> 00:12:48.858
one, as per our previous publication on "Annals of Oncology."

210
00:12:49.998 --> 00:12:53.678
So basically, these results shows there are two

211
00:12:53.778 --> 00:12:57.178
different biological states, responders with a more

212
00:12:57.398 --> 00:12:59.978
immune permissive microenvironment and

213
00:13:00.818 --> 00:13:04.578
more active cytotoxic engagement, and non-responders

214
00:13:05.518 --> 00:13:09.378
with stromal constraint and with features which are consistent

215
00:13:09.438 --> 00:13:10.678
with immune exclusion.

216
00:13:14.098 --> 00:13:14.638
To conclude,

217
00:13:15.738 --> 00:13:19.678
a non-operative management strategy following three months

218
00:13:20.218 --> 00:13:23.158
of tremelimumab plus durvalumab in

219
00:13:23.218 --> 00:13:26.998
resectable MSI high gastric or

220
00:13:27.038 --> 00:13:30.598
gastroesophageal junction cancer patients in carefully

221
00:13:30.658 --> 00:13:34.558
selected patients is a viable option, is safe,

222
00:13:35.298 --> 00:13:38.738
and has been already endorsed by NCCN in their guidelines.

223
00:13:40.518 --> 00:13:43.718
However, the optimal strategy for these patients

224
00:13:44.598 --> 00:13:48.368
in terms of treatment duration, treatment regimen, and

225
00:13:48.438 --> 00:13:52.338
treatment goal still needs to be established in

226
00:13:52.398 --> 00:13:55.858
larger randomized or adaptive trials.

227
00:13:57.378 --> 00:13:57.978
And finally,

228
00:13:59.058 --> 00:14:03.018
this approach in clinical practice would require shared

229
00:14:03.028 --> 00:14:04.338
decision-making with patient

230
00:14:05.478 --> 00:14:09.418
with a careful balance between the intensive surveillance which is needed in a

231
00:14:09.518 --> 00:14:13.398
non-operative management pathway and a timely selective

232
00:14:13.578 --> 00:14:16.058
surgery when and if needed.

233
00:14:18.678 --> 00:14:22.278
I want to thank all the patients and their families for their trust,

234
00:14:22.898 --> 00:14:26.818
for participating in our trial. I want to thank Gono Foundation, our

235
00:14:26.878 --> 00:14:30.398
sponsor, and all the investigators across the Italian

236
00:14:30.958 --> 00:14:32.078
participating centers.

237
00:14:33.128 --> 00:14:36.838
A huge thanks goes to the GI oncology team at

238
00:14:36.878 --> 00:14:38.438
Istituto Nazionale Tumori in Milan,

239
00:14:39.558 --> 00:14:43.388
and especially I want to thank Dr. Raimondi who co-lead the project with me, Dr.

240
00:14:43.678 --> 00:14:47.298
Manca for his invaluable support in results analysis,

241
00:14:47.998 --> 00:14:50.598
and obviously my mentor, Dr. Filippo Pietrantonio,

242
00:14:51.487 --> 00:14:55.158
who's been the driving force behind all of this and who

243
00:14:55.258 --> 00:14:59.138
instilled in me the value and pride of conducting academic

244
00:14:59.198 --> 00:15:01.738
research. So thank you all for your attention.

245
00:15:10.658 --> 00:15:14.248
Thank you so much. Next, I'd like to introduce the discussant, Dr.

246
00:15:14.818 --> 00:15:18.328
Yelena Janjigian from Memorial Sloan Kettering, to share her

247
00:15:18.358 --> 00:15:20.038
perspectives on these results.

248
00:15:27.378 --> 00:15:30.898
Good morning and thank you for the opportunity to discuss this important

249
00:15:31.458 --> 00:15:32.218
abstract.

250
00:15:34.318 --> 00:15:35.518
These are my disclosures.

251
00:15:37.258 --> 00:15:38.498
And of course,

252
00:15:39.818 --> 00:15:42.098
role of MSI varies across tumor types.

253
00:15:42.218 --> 00:15:46.058
We're here to discuss gastric and gastroesophageal

254
00:15:46.078 --> 00:15:49.987
cancer, where the rate of MSI tumors is approximately

255
00:15:50.098 --> 00:15:53.758
10% in early stage, which is the disease we're discussing

256
00:15:53.798 --> 00:15:57.658
today, and 3% in metastatic. Overall, these patients have

257
00:15:57.738 --> 00:16:01.398
excellent prognosis, so many of them would be

258
00:16:01.438 --> 00:16:05.278
cured with surgery alone. So why are we discussing this

259
00:16:05.378 --> 00:16:09.258
option? And this important study today we're discussing will

260
00:16:09.298 --> 00:16:12.308
be the potential to replace surgery and

261
00:16:12.778 --> 00:16:14.808
non-operative management, which is critical.

262
00:16:15.698 --> 00:16:19.398
Can early dual checkpoint blockade replace surgery in MSI high

263
00:16:19.678 --> 00:16:23.348
gastric cancer? So what we saw today is that after three months of

264
00:16:23.418 --> 00:16:27.218
therapy with durvalumab and a single dose of tremelimumab, we

265
00:16:27.228 --> 00:16:30.378
achieved 71% complete response clinically,

266
00:16:31.078 --> 00:16:34.698
94% progression-free survival, and 100% overall

267
00:16:34.818 --> 00:16:36.758
survival, although the follow-up is short.

268
00:16:37.178 --> 00:16:41.038
And most importantly, 70% of patients were able to go

269
00:16:41.078 --> 00:16:43.958
without surgery, which is potentially life altering.

270
00:16:44.338 --> 00:16:47.838
Gastrectomy, we can all agree, is a life-altering operation.

271
00:16:49.338 --> 00:16:52.558
Where are we currently in the paradigm for this disease?

272
00:16:52.658 --> 00:16:56.368
Well, Matterhorn study in the last year changed practice for

273
00:16:56.518 --> 00:17:00.338
all comers, including MSS and MSI tumors, demonstrating

274
00:17:00.598 --> 00:17:04.538
a survival benefit for perioperative chemoimmunotherapy

275
00:17:05.138 --> 00:17:07.858
in early stage esophageal and gastric cancer.

276
00:17:08.778 --> 00:17:12.479
More importantly, pathologic complete response does translate to

277
00:17:12.518 --> 00:17:16.407
survival benefit, and so this is an important factor to consider as you're

278
00:17:16.439 --> 00:17:19.979
interpreting the study. And for all comers, the complete

279
00:17:19.998 --> 00:17:23.709
pathologic response is approximately 19% with anti-PD-1 plus

280
00:17:23.798 --> 00:17:27.558
FLOT, and the major pathologic response is approximately

281
00:17:27.638 --> 00:17:29.238
seen in 30% of patients.

282
00:17:31.518 --> 00:17:33.658
So what about PD-1 blockade alone?

283
00:17:34.058 --> 00:17:37.878
Importantly, we know that non-operative management is already included and

284
00:17:37.938 --> 00:17:41.878
guidelines supported across several guidelines, including NCCN, but

285
00:17:41.938 --> 00:17:44.178
the response rate varies by tumor type.

286
00:17:44.238 --> 00:17:47.698
Of course, mismatch repair is a pan-tumor

287
00:17:47.758 --> 00:17:51.118
biomarker, but when you're treating with rectal cancer versus

288
00:17:51.158 --> 00:17:55.098
gastroesophageal cancer, the complete response rate to anti-PD1 alone is

289
00:17:55.138 --> 00:17:58.458
quite variable. And for our disease, unfortunately,

290
00:17:58.758 --> 00:18:02.698
60% of patients still needed surgery if you were to

291
00:18:02.738 --> 00:18:05.038
pursue a durvalumab, for example,

292
00:18:05.078 --> 00:18:08.866
aloneSingle versus dual neoadjuvant

293
00:18:08.906 --> 00:18:12.846
blockade is an important question, and what appears to be that dual checkpoint

294
00:18:12.886 --> 00:18:16.426
blockade will be important and required if you will be

295
00:18:16.806 --> 00:18:18.366
approaching chemotherapy-free

296
00:18:19.246 --> 00:18:23.126
approach to achieve organ preservation in gastroesophageal cancer.

297
00:18:23.666 --> 00:18:27.296
We need CTLA-4 here to expand and

298
00:18:27.346 --> 00:18:29.226
reactivate tumor-specific immunity.

299
00:18:29.766 --> 00:18:33.146
And as you see here, again, inter-trial comparison, but the

300
00:18:33.186 --> 00:18:34.106
dostarlimab arm

301
00:18:35.346 --> 00:18:36.426
group had a similar

302
00:18:37.326 --> 00:18:41.206
number of gastroesophageal cancer patients, so it's helpful to see these

303
00:18:41.246 --> 00:18:45.146
numbers. Response with dual checkpoint blockade that Alberto

304
00:18:45.206 --> 00:18:47.326
just presented appears to be numerically better.

305
00:18:48.306 --> 00:18:52.046
And again, there's 20%, roughly, increase in the complete

306
00:18:52.106 --> 00:18:55.346
response rate if you add at least one dose of

307
00:18:55.446 --> 00:18:56.285
CTLA-4.

308
00:18:57.826 --> 00:19:00.286
So what are the aspects of the INFINITY study?

309
00:19:00.326 --> 00:19:03.966
Of course, it's an academic study, and again, congratulations to the Gano group

310
00:19:04.346 --> 00:19:07.666
for getting this done. It's a small study, short follow-up.

311
00:19:08.266 --> 00:19:12.226
And of course, T4 tumors were excluded, because those are higher

312
00:19:12.306 --> 00:19:15.046
risk and they may need more time to treatment.

313
00:19:15.306 --> 00:19:19.286
But it's very elegant design and really adaptive, looking

314
00:19:19.306 --> 00:19:22.616
at important biomarkers of predictive of response and

315
00:19:22.686 --> 00:19:23.326
resistance.

316
00:19:24.886 --> 00:19:28.596
So the most innovative aspect of this study is, of course, non-operative

317
00:19:28.686 --> 00:19:32.546
management. And to be able to convince the patients and, of

318
00:19:32.586 --> 00:19:36.566
course, the surgeons not to have an operation is a true

319
00:19:37.406 --> 00:19:40.686
important effort of the multidisciplinary group.

320
00:19:41.086 --> 00:19:45.056
So the traditional paradigm has been chemotherapy followed by surgery and adjuvant

321
00:19:45.126 --> 00:19:46.886
therapy in this disease. The

322
00:19:47.846 --> 00:19:50.346
newest paradigm is to add immunotherapy,

323
00:19:51.226 --> 00:19:54.786
and then the risk adaptive paradigm that you saw today

324
00:19:55.166 --> 00:19:58.866
is perhaps to start with a short course of immunotherapy,

325
00:19:59.386 --> 00:20:02.786
do response assessment, and then decide what to do next.

326
00:20:03.226 --> 00:20:07.006
So the multimodal surveillance will need to reflect this

327
00:20:07.046 --> 00:20:10.406
complex paradigm and to be able to adjust

328
00:20:11.126 --> 00:20:13.226
to therapies along the way.

329
00:20:15.126 --> 00:20:19.066
So the biomarker data from this study really helps

330
00:20:19.126 --> 00:20:23.026
support and create a safety net

331
00:20:23.346 --> 00:20:27.046
for non-operative management. And there is myeloid-rich

332
00:20:27.106 --> 00:20:31.006
suppressive TME that is very important to assess, and of course,

333
00:20:31.066 --> 00:20:34.966
circulating tumor DNA using newer assays will improve both

334
00:20:35.066 --> 00:20:38.436
our sensitivity and specificity for predicting of response.

335
00:20:39.366 --> 00:20:43.226
Unlike some other diseases, endoscopies are relatively easy to do, so

336
00:20:43.266 --> 00:20:46.906
local assessment and serial biopsies and, of course, functional imaging

337
00:20:47.066 --> 00:20:49.046
is very helpful for our cancers.

338
00:20:51.066 --> 00:20:54.326
So how are we comparing then to

339
00:20:55.306 --> 00:20:57.426
the difference across tumor types?

340
00:20:57.755 --> 00:21:01.626
And of course, the toxicity profile in this regimen is quite

341
00:21:01.786 --> 00:21:05.106
favorable. And as I mentioned, higher complete response rate really

342
00:21:05.166 --> 00:21:09.006
suggests that anti PD-1 alone is not sufficient for our

343
00:21:09.046 --> 00:21:12.626
disease. In fact, using chemoimmunotherapy,

344
00:21:13.166 --> 00:21:16.826
it would be the only way to do anti PD-1 therapy alone, but

345
00:21:17.126 --> 00:21:20.486
combined PD-1, CTLA-4 blockade would be useful.

346
00:21:22.406 --> 00:21:26.046
So MSI tumors demonstrate the curative potential of

347
00:21:26.106 --> 00:21:30.066
immunotherapy first in neoadjuvant setting, and you saw the

348
00:21:30.106 --> 00:21:31.366
curves on the left

349
00:21:32.446 --> 00:21:36.046
to look at the overall outcomes for, for

350
00:21:36.086 --> 00:21:40.066
example, MSI high tumors using durvetrumab, two-year PFS

351
00:21:40.106 --> 00:21:43.886
is 94%, while MSS surgery and

352
00:21:43.966 --> 00:21:47.046
MSI surgery alone groups are reflected here.

353
00:21:47.066 --> 00:21:51.046
But surgery alone, the two-year disease-free survival is 84%.

354
00:21:51.946 --> 00:21:55.906
So what about operating on them first and then only

355
00:21:55.966 --> 00:21:59.146
treating if you have MRD, so ctDNA positive setting?

356
00:21:59.546 --> 00:22:02.126
Perhaps you would then avoid over-treating patients.

357
00:22:02.386 --> 00:22:04.266
That's a question that was raised.

358
00:22:04.726 --> 00:22:08.486
And looking on the right, this is a trial we presented

359
00:22:08.786 --> 00:22:12.466
at ACR last year, that if you are

360
00:22:12.506 --> 00:22:16.406
ctDNA positive in MSI tumors after resection, yes,

361
00:22:16.566 --> 00:22:20.466
you could clear ctDNA with six months of, in this case, pembrolizumab,

362
00:22:20.906 --> 00:22:22.846
and yes, you can improve on your

363
00:22:23.785 --> 00:22:25.626
progression-free or disease-free survival.

364
00:22:26.086 --> 00:22:29.986
At two years, the disease-free survival with adjuvant PD-1 therapy

365
00:22:30.286 --> 00:22:33.876
was 92%. But despite initial

366
00:22:33.986 --> 00:22:36.606
ctDNA clearance, 38% of patients,

367
00:22:37.606 --> 00:22:41.026
eventually the ctDNA went up, and they

368
00:22:41.046 --> 00:22:44.516
recurred. And again, highlighting that if you're MRD positive,

369
00:22:44.906 --> 00:22:48.806
even in MSI setting, it's a very high-risk population, and six months of

370
00:22:48.926 --> 00:22:50.346
adjuvant therapy is not sufficient.

371
00:22:50.886 --> 00:22:54.446
More importantly, treating the tumor while the tumor is still in place in

372
00:22:54.506 --> 00:22:57.886
neoadjuvant setting appears to be the really the critical

373
00:22:58.346 --> 00:23:02.286
step to mounting anti-tumor response, avoiding surgery,

374
00:23:02.386 --> 00:23:05.586
perhaps, and durably curing these patients.

375
00:23:08.086 --> 00:23:11.366
So in conclusion, what we saw today is that dual immune checkpoint

376
00:23:11.686 --> 00:23:14.806
blockade induces durable complete responses.

377
00:23:14.846 --> 00:23:16.886
And again, congratulations to the Gano group

378
00:23:17.786 --> 00:23:21.746
for this excellent study. Non-operative management was really the

379
00:23:22.766 --> 00:23:23.406
breakthrough

380
00:23:24.586 --> 00:23:28.326
demonstration of this approach to allow organ preservation.

381
00:23:28.366 --> 00:23:32.146
And in the modern era, even for MSS tumor-specific

382
00:23:32.246 --> 00:23:35.846
studies, if you're writing a consent form, the

383
00:23:35.886 --> 00:23:38.686
patients expect to see non-operative option in there.

384
00:23:39.006 --> 00:23:41.226
So that's a very modern approach to therapy.

385
00:23:41.806 --> 00:23:45.666
Combination therapy appears to be necessary, and dual immune checkpoint blockade

386
00:23:45.686 --> 00:23:49.566
does address some of that tumor heterogeneity that we see in our

387
00:23:49.576 --> 00:23:53.486
disease, but not all. And future trials should integrate biomarkers,

388
00:23:53.626 --> 00:23:57.106
response adaptive therapy, and personalized escalation or

389
00:23:57.166 --> 00:23:59.786
de-escalation therapy. So the final take

390
00:24:00.886 --> 00:24:04.866
point home is that early immunotherapy while

391
00:24:04.906 --> 00:24:08.366
the tumor is still in place will redefine the current

392
00:24:08.426 --> 00:24:12.076
standard for MSI high cancers, shifting from traditional

393
00:24:12.126 --> 00:24:15.086
approaches of surgical approaches to non-operative

394
00:24:15.166 --> 00:24:19.070
management.And the outstanding questions for our field is: Is

395
00:24:19.130 --> 00:24:22.710
chemotherapy still necessary for MSI-high gastric and

396
00:24:22.750 --> 00:24:26.510
gastroesophageal cancers? Because that's the gold standard with the Matterhorn

397
00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:30.350
data, and we are awaiting the MSI subset from Matterhorn

398
00:24:30.430 --> 00:24:33.650
FLOT durvalumab-treated cohort to see how it would

399
00:24:33.690 --> 00:24:36.730
compare to the dual immune checkpoint cohort.

400
00:24:37.290 --> 00:24:40.260
And can immunotherapy strategies truly replace surgery,

401
00:24:41.230 --> 00:24:43.110
and how do we adapt to this regimen?

402
00:24:43.970 --> 00:24:47.550
So in the past, we treated patients with surgery and chemotherapy.

403
00:24:47.930 --> 00:24:51.890
Now we're doing FLOT plus anti-PD-1, and the future adaptive

404
00:24:51.950 --> 00:24:55.590
therapy could involve dual immune checkpoint blockade first, then

405
00:24:55.670 --> 00:24:59.330
your early response assessment. And if you are having high-risk

406
00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:02.850
features and you're not seeing that you're on your way to complete

407
00:25:02.910 --> 00:25:05.770
response, you could pivot to chemoimmunotherapy,

408
00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:10.070
and eventually, I suspect some patients will still need surgery.

409
00:25:10.690 --> 00:25:14.590
Thank you for your attention. It's really an amazing opportunity to

410
00:25:14.630 --> 00:25:18.170
work with these bright talent across the globe,

411
00:25:18.330 --> 00:25:18.690
and

412
00:25:20.050 --> 00:25:23.029
congratulations again.

413
00:25:29.330 --> 00:25:29.650
Great.

414
00:25:30.490 --> 00:25:34.380
We're going to welcome some questions for five minutes of

