1502
01:31:13.460 --> 01:31:17.220
Immune checkpoint inhibitors have significantly improved outcomes in patients with

1503
01:31:17.280 --> 01:31:21.260
non-small cell lung cancer. However, resistance to anti-PD-1 or

1504
01:31:21.340 --> 01:31:24.400
PD-L1 therapy still remains a major clinical challenge.

1505
01:31:25.080 --> 01:31:28.380
Immunotherapy resistance is broadly classified into two groups:

1506
01:31:28.860 --> 01:31:32.130
primary resistance, where there is no measurable response to immunotherapy,

1507
01:31:32.380 --> 01:31:36.200
typically within six months, and acquired resistance, where there's an initial

1508
01:31:36.240 --> 01:31:39.920
clinical benefit of at least six months followed by disease progression.

1509
01:31:40.950 --> 01:31:44.600
Previous studies have identified several molecular features associated with

1510
01:31:44.640 --> 01:31:48.040
immunotherapy resistance, including KRAS/SDK11

1511
01:31:48.080 --> 01:31:52.020
co-mutations that promote an immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment,

1512
01:31:52.600 --> 01:31:56.580
as well as inactivating mutations in genes such as KEAP1, V2M,

1513
01:31:56.860 --> 01:31:57.940
JAK1, JAK2,

1514
01:31:58.760 --> 01:32:00.140
PTEN, and β-catenin,

1515
01:32:00.980 --> 01:32:04.840
which confer tumor immune exclusion or loss of responsiveness

